<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "What are running pace zones?", answer: "Running pace zones are ranges of training paces that correspond to different physiological adaptations. There are typically 5 zones: Zone 1 (Easy/Recovery) at 125-140% of threshold pace, Zone 2 (Aerobic/Endurance) at 110-125%, Zone 3 (Tempo/Threshold) at 97-110%, Zone 4 (VO2max/Interval) at 88-97%, and Zone 5 (Speed/Repetition) at 78-88%. Training in the right zone ensures you stress the correct energy systems." },
  { question: "How do I find my threshold pace?", answer: "Threshold pace is the fastest pace you can sustain for about 60 minutes in a race. You can estimate it from a recent race time: 5K pace is roughly 94% of threshold, 10K pace is close to threshold, and half marathon pace is about 4% slower than threshold. Alternatively, run a 20-minute time trial at maximum sustainable effort; your average pace is approximately your threshold pace." },
  { question: "What is the difference between threshold pace and race pace?", answer: "Threshold pace (also called lactate threshold pace) is the pace at which lactate begins to accumulate faster than it can be cleared. It corresponds roughly to 10K race pace for recreational runners and is slightly faster than half marathon pace. For elite runners, threshold pace is closer to half marathon pace because they can sustain a higher percentage of their threshold for longer." },
  { question: "How much of my training should be in Zone 2?", answer: "Most elite coaches recommend the 80/20 rule: approximately 80% of your weekly running volume should be in Zone 1-2 (easy/aerobic), with only 20% in Zones 3-5 (moderate to hard). This polarized approach builds a strong aerobic base while allowing adequate recovery, leading to better long-term improvement than doing most runs at moderate intensity." },
  { question: "Can I use these zones for treadmill running?", answer: "Yes, these zones apply to treadmill running. However, treadmill pace often feels slightly easier due to lack of wind resistance and the belt moving underfoot. A common adjustment is to set the treadmill incline to 1% to approximate outdoor running effort. You can also use heart rate monitoring alongside pace zones for more accurate intensity control indoors." }
]) %>

